As soon as Rome recovered from the Etruscan defeat, she became engaged in wars with the neigh- bouring peoples. Volscians and Aurumans, AEquians, Sabines, all appear at war with her, the names of her soes varying according as the annalists drew from the records of one Roman family or another. &Vhether these fought as clients or allies of the Etruscans, or on their own account as rival claimants for the supremacy which the removal of Etruscan pressure had thrown open to competition‚ it is impossible to say. But tradition and inherent probability would incline us to believe that the struggle must have been a fierce one, and that Rome must often have been near destruc- tion.
